@NODE "Einf" "Introduction"
@TOC "MAIN"

WBInfo is a replacement for the information-window of the workbench.
There are three different ways to use WBInfo:

 · WBInfo patches the wbinfo() routine of the workbench.library.
 · WBInfo can also be used as a command.
 · It's also possible to use WBInfo as an internal @{b}module for Scalos@{ub}!

WBInfo also supports NewIcons directly via the newicon.library and it's
possible to control it as a commodity  via Exchange! It also has some 
additional @{"features" LINK "Features"}, that do a lot of work for you.

WBInfo requires @{"MUI" LINK "MUI"}!!!
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Install" "Installation"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{u}Requirements:@{uu}

 · Amiga with 68000-68060 CPU
 · OS 2.1 (v38) +
 · MUI 3.8 +

@{u}Recommended:@{uu}

 · Amiga with 68020 CPU +
 · OS 3.1 (v40) +
 · Scalos
 · newicon.library
 · wbstart.library

@{u}@{b}For installation:@{ub}@{uu}

Please use the Installer-script, which comes with WBInfo!

@{u}manual installation:@{uu}

WBInfo should be copied into your SYS:WBStartup/ -drawer, if you want to use WBInfo as a Patch
for the Workbench or DOpus.
You can also use WBInfo as a Shell/WB command.
Then i recommend to copy WBInfo into your C: drawer.

Simple enter  WBInfo <filename> or run it via WB using "extended selection" with the <Shift> key.

Then WBInfo won't patch the workbench.library and you save memory (about 60kb),
but it will slow down WBInfo, because it has to be loaded from your Hardisk everytime!

@{u}Scalos:@{uu}

WBInfo can be used as an internal module of Scalos. The only thing you have to do,
is rename WBInfo to "Information.module" and move it into "Scalos:Modules/"!


@{b}@{u}Important!!!@{uu}
If you install WBInfo by your own, don't forget to copy the right .catalog file
into your Locale:<language>/ directory!
@{ub}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Konf" "Configuration"
@TOC "MAIN"

Since version 2.5, wbinfo can be configurated via Tooltypes!
In WBInfo's Tooltypes you can add your favourite default Tools,
which'll be in a PopUp Menu above the Default Tool String!

To add your own default Tools, simply edit the Tooltype

@{b}DEFTOOLS=@{ub}
after the keyword DEFTOOLS, you can add your own Tools!
First the program-title, then a ',' and after that the program-path.
The next entry must be seperated via a '|'!
Please notice th following:

 1.) It's @{b}not possible to fill in more than 256 chars@{ub} in one Tooltype-row
     and so the program-titles and the paths should not be too long.
     (every entry (e.g. path) can't be longer than 32 chars!)

 2.) It's @{b}not possible to add more than five custom-entries@{ub}! So only
     choose the most important programs.

 3.) The default settings features (the most important) programs like MultiView,
     MuchMore, More, IconX and Installer! To use the default-settings
     you must set the DEFTOOLS-Tooltype in brackets!
     (If you think, that another default setting in better, then contact us!)

Example:

@{b}DEFTOOLS=MultiView,Sys:Utilities/Multiview|Visage,C:Visage|CyberView,Sys:Utilities/CyberView@{ub}


@{b}Some notes about the usage:@{ub}

Above the Tooltype-Listview there's also a PopUpMenu (can be activated
via right mouse button) which has some entrys for multiple-change!
(e.g. delete all tooltypes, toggle all...)

Above the default-tools string (only with project-icons) there is also
a PopUpMenu available, which give use the chance to insert your
favourite default-tools! This PopUpMenu is configurable via Tooltype (see above)

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Kompak" "Compatibility"
@TOC "MAIN"

Incompatibilities? Bugs? Suggestions? Drop @{"us" LINK "Adresse"} a few lines!

WBInfo uses the @{b}newicon.library@{ub} to support the NewIcon-Standard.
It's not necessary to run the NewIcon-Patch. This is good, if you use a Workbench-Replacement
(e.g. DirectoryOPUS, Scalos) which also supports NewIcons!

WBInfo also supports Scalos by giving the User the chance to edit Tooltypes with Disk, Drawer
and Trashcan Icons. It may also be interesting that WBInfo can be used as a Scalos-module, too!

@{b}If there are any problems while calling the MUI-Settings, try to increase the Stack.
In this version the default Stack is set to 16000 bytes!@{ub}

!!! If you use WBInfo as Information.module with Scalos, you should
increase the stack too!
1.) Set the Stack of the Information.module Icon to 16000bytes or higher
2.) Increase the Stack in the ScalosMenu preferences. (entry iconinfo)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Features" "Features"
@TOC "MAIN"

WBInfo features:

 · @{b}MUI@{ub} Interface (configurable, fontadaptive, resizeable)
 · @{b}Rename@{ub} a file (filename is shown in a String-Gadget and can be changed!)
 · change the @{b}Icontype@{ub} (The Icontype (Project, Tool, ...) is shown in a Cycle-Gadget and can be
   changed, too!)
 · @{b}NewIcon Support@{ub} (WBInfo supports the NewIcon-System directly, NewIcon-Tooltypes are hidden
   and the Icon will also be loaded without NewIcon-Patch)
 · @{b}GetVersion@{ub} (On Tool-Icons the version of a program can be checked via a gadget.
   WBInfo searchs in the file for the "$VER:"-String. If it can't be found, WBInfo only show "???")
 · @{b}GetSize@{ub} (With Trashcan and Drawer-Icons, there is a Gadget which checks the Number of Bytes,
   in the current Directory)
 · @{b}Hidden-Bit support@{ub} (PatchHidden Support, doesn't work with Scalos)
 · @{b}Tooltype-Toggle@{ub} (activate/deactivate Tooltypes via Gadget or double-click!)
 · @{b}Scalos Support@{ub} (WBInfo also has Tooltypes with Drawer, Trashcan and Disk-Icons
   and is Information.module compatible.)
 · @{b}PopUp-Menus@{ub} for Default Tools and Tooltypes.
 · @{b}Extended Disk Information@{ub} Information about Device, Unit, FileSystem and Protection
 · @{b}EmptyTrash@{ub} (On Trashcan-Icons there is a Button, for the "empty-trash" function!)
 · @{b}Format Disk@{ub} (On Disk-Icons there is a Button, for formatting the Disk!)
 · @{b}Locale Support@{ub} (if you have OS2.1 or better you can use language-catalogs for WBInfo)
 · and much, much more! ;-)

@ENDNODE


